The price prediction model of Airbnb in New York¶

Airbnb is the largest online short-term rental servies in the world (Falk, Larpin and Scaglione, 2019).By 2018, Airbnb has 4.5 million listings in the world. Price and location are the most important parameters in Airbnb literature . In recent years, many scholars showed their interest of Airbnb price setting. Some studies have found that prices of Airbnb accommodations are related to the internal characteristics of accommodation and external factors. Some studies consider the type of room as factors;location specific factors can also effect the price of accommodations (Chattopadhyay and Mitra, 2019).Besides, characteristics of Airbnb host is also important. Host has more than one listings can be expected to achieve higher price (Chen and Xie, 2017).

This study uses 2019 New York Airbnb data, which is download from Kaggle. The aim of this study is to explore the data and build price regression models to predict the price of Airbnb. This study is going to present the distribution of Airbnb accommodations in New York City and explain the characteristics of them. I will practice data cleaning, regression algorithms and feature engineering to achieve the lowest prediction error for the final model.

Loading data¶

The dataset has 48895 observations with 16 variables.There are six categorical variables and then numerical variables. It contains external characteristics of Airbnb accommodations, such as location, boroughs, as well as internal characteristics like room type, available days. Some individual variables have to be drop, because this study will not involve individual characteristics in the price prediction model.

Data cleaning¶

In order to build regression model, it requires cleaning the null values and dropping irrelevant and insignificant features.Some features related to individual information need to be dropped, such as id,name, host name. This study focus on the neighbourhood group levels, so neighbourhood feature has been dropped. There are three features related to reviews. This study drops 'last_reviews' feature, which is related to date. There are four features containing null values. For "reviews_per_month" columns, null values occur where no reviews were given in the place.Therefore, I simply append it with 0 for null values, which means there is 0 rate of reviews per month.

Data exploration¶

This section is trying to explore and explain features in our dataset. It`s going to show the distribution of each feature and geographical distribution based on attributes.

Neighbourhood group¶

The chart below shows the distribution of Airbnb in New York. Most of Airbnb accommodations are located in Manhattan and Brooklyn.Staten Island only have 373 accommodations. From the map, it`s clear that Mahattan has the smallest land areas but has the most Airbnb accomodations and the highest density. The reason is that Manhattan is the business center as well as tourist destination.

Minimum stay¶

The range of minimum stay is from 0 to 400 days. There are only some accommodations requiring stay more than 400 days. This feature has skewed distribution, which may cause problems when building regression model. I made log transformation to make the distribution closer to normal. In the next section, I will examine if there is any outlier and remove them.

Reviews per month¶

The distribution of reviews per month is also highly skewed. There are lots of Airbnb accommodations only getting less than 10 reviews a month. There is also a long tail that some Airbnb accommodations got many reviews a month. I made square root transformation to try to make the distribution more normal.

Price¶

Price is the dependent variable of our regression model. Most of price of Airbnb accommodations are from 0 to 500. The long tail indicates that there are few accommodations have high price. I made logarithmic transformation to get the normal distribution and dropped extreme values.From the Q-Q plot is easily to tell that the points are almost identical to line y = x after logarithmic transformation and removing extreme values. Therefore, this study only involves Airbnb accommodations which price is under 500.

price_type=[]
name_list=['Entire home/apt', 'Private room', 'Shared room']
for x in roomtype_price:
    i=x.describe(percentiles=[.25, .50, .75])
    i=i.iloc[3:]
    i.reset_index(inplace=True)
    i.rename(columns={'index':'Stats'}, inplace=True)
    price_type.append(i)
price_type[0].rename(columns={'price':name_list[0]}, inplace=True)
price_type[1].rename(columns={'price':name_list[1]}, inplace=True)
price_type[2].rename(columns={'price':name_list[2]}, inplace=True)
stat_df1=price_type
stat_df1=[df.set_index('Stats') for df in stat_df1]
stat_df1=stat_df1[0].join(stat_df1[1:])

Bivariate correlations¶

The matrix shows the correlations between numerical features in the dataset. There is no strong correlations between features. The number of reviews is 60% correlated with the number of reviews per month; the price is 30% correlated with longitude, because the high price accommodations are located at the Manhattan. The host id conlume need to dropped, because it is not related to price.

In order to build regression model, it needs to remove outliers as well as examine multicollinearity. The scatter plots show the correlations of four numerical variables with price. The outliers will appear at the right of red line. There is no outlier observed in the plot. Multicollinearity will help to measure the relationship between explanatory variables in multiple regression. If there is multicollinearity occurs, these highly related input variables should be eliminated from the model.None of the result is closed to zero. It means there is no multicollinearity in the data.

Feature engineering¶

In order to build regression model, it needs to encode the categorical variables to number. There are two categorical variables included in the model: neighbourhood group and room type.

In [137]:
def Encode(df):
    for column in df.columns[df.columns.isin(['neighbourhood_group', 'room_type'])]:
        df[column] = df[column].factorize()[0]
    return df

df_en = Encode(df.copy())

Regression model¶

After data cleaning and feature engineering, the price prediction model includes nine independent variables.The data has been split in train and test sets with 80-20 ratio. We use the training set to train the model and use the testing model to test the accuracy of the model. The train set has 38128 observations and test set has 9532 observations. For the start, I will try the basic regression model: Linear regression.

Regularization¶

Lasso regression, ridge regression and ElasicNet regression are built to avoid over-fitting of basic linear regression model. The first step is to find a value of alpha that minimizes the train and test error. GridSearchCV algorithm is used to find the best alpha for each model.

ElasticNet regression combines both ridge and lasso regression. It needs to set ratio between ridge and lasso to get a better combination of both.

In [158]:
import math
import sklearn.model_selection as GridSearchCV
import sklearn.model_selection as ms

ridge=Ridge()
parameters= {'alpha':[x for x in range(1,101)]}

ridge_reg=ms.GridSearchCV(ridge, param_grid=parameters, scoring='neg_mean_squared_error', cv=15)
ridge_reg.fit(x_train,y_train)
print("The best value of Alpha is: ",ridge_reg.best_params_)
print("The best score achieved with Alpha=11 is: ",math.sqrt(-ridge_reg.best_score_))
ridge_pred=math.sqrt(-ridge_reg.best_score_)

The best value of Alpha is:  {'alpha': 1}
The best score achieved with Alpha=11 is:  71.5299548645043

The result shows the relationship between price and nine independent variables. Overall, the fit of coefficient of determination is weak, with 0.28 r-square value.There is only 28% accommodation fitting the model.But we still can find some relationships between price and independent variables from coefficients.

First, the price may increase when the latitude increases and may decrease when longitude increase. Manhattan is located in the north of New York, which has the highest range of Airbnb accommodation. It can be predicted the accommodation located in the northeast are more expensive than that in the southwest. Staten Island is located in the southwest of New York, which has the least accommodations and lower price among five boroughs. Accommodations in Mahhattan will have higher price than that in other four boroughs. For room type, entire room/apt is expected to have higher price than private room and shared room. The price grew in inverse proportion to the minimum stay nights. The accommodations which requires to stay more nights have lower price than that requires to stay short.The accommodations which have more reviews are expected to have lower price. But accommodations which got more reviews in each month will have higher price than others. The accommodations owned by the host who have many accommodations will have higher price. What`s more, the accommodations which are available for more days in a year will have higher price than that only available a couple of days.

Conclusion¶

In this study, the determinants of Airbnb accommodation prices were examined based on internal and external characteristics. For regression analysis, nine variables are considered in the model. This study compares four different regression models and choose the model with the least errors as the final model. The linear regression model showes the relationship between price and nine independent variables. Longitude and latitude are the most important variables. It can indicate that the location is a important feature when we predict price. Room type is also important when predict accommodation price. Entire home/apt is expected to have higher price than private room and shared room.

Some limitations of the study needs to be considered. First, the goodness of fit is weak. The most important reason is that this study only consider the variables within the dataset.Some scholar fins that the price of Airbnb accommodations depend on host reputations, cancellation policy and local amenities. What`s more, for commercial accommodations, the needs of customers are also important. It is related to other external characteristics, like transportation, tourist sites(Falk, Larpin and Scaglione, 2019).

Reference¶

Chattopadhyay, M. and Mitra, S., 2019. Do airbnb host listing attributes influence room pricing homogenously?. International Journal of Hospitality Management, 81, pp.54-64.

Chen, Y. and Xie, K., 2017. Consumer valuation of Airbnb listings: a hedonic pricing approach. International Journal of Contemporary Hospitality Management, 29(9), pp.2405-2424.

Falk, M., Larpin, B. and Scaglione, M., 2019. The role of specific attributes in determining prices of Airbnb listings in rural and urban locations. International Journal of Hospitality Management, 83, pp.132-140.
